The rule of three (or four or five) is a guideline for implementing certain methods in a C++ class that manages dynamically-allocated resources (e.g. heap memory). Specifically, it states that if you implement any of the following methods, you should also implement the others:

1. Destructor (the "first" method)
2. Copy constructor
3. Copy assignment operator
4. Move constructor (optional, part of "rule of five")
5. Move assignment operator (optional, part of "rule of five")

The reason for this guideline is that if a class manages dynamic resources, there can be subtle interactions between these methods that can lead to bugs if one or more of them is not implemented correctly. By implementing all of them, you ensure that the class behaves correctly in all possible situations.

Here's an example implementation of a class `Clone` that manages a dynamically-allocated pointer:

```
class Clone {
public:
    Clone(int value) {
        ptr = new int(value);
    }
    ~Clone() {
        delete ptr;
    }
    Clone(const Clone& other) {
        ptr = new int(*other.ptr);
    }
    Clone& operator=(const Clone& other) {
        if (this != &other) {
            delete ptr;
            ptr = new int(*other.ptr);
        }
        return *this;
    }
    Clone(Clone&& other) {
        ptr = other.ptr;
        other.ptr = nullptr;
    }
    Clone& operator=(Clone&& other) {
        if (this != &other) {
            delete ptr;
            ptr = other.ptr;
            other.ptr = nullptr;
        }
        return *this;
    }
private:
    int* ptr;
};
```

In this implementation, the class `Clone` has an integer pointer `ptr`, allocated in the constructor and deallocated in the destructor. The copy constructor and copy assignment operator allocate a new integer, copy the value from the source object, and deallocate the old integer. The move constructor and move assignment operator simply transfer ownership of the integer pointer from the source to the destination object. Note that the move methods are optional and are not strictly necessary for this class, as it doesn't contain any expensive-to-move resources.

The asterisk (*) in the declaration of T * start and T * end limits the use of the function. Is this true?

template <class T>
int adding(T * start, T * end) {
    int result = 0;
    while ( start != end ) {
        result += *start;
        ++start;
    }
    return result;
}

